      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the memory leak! You've found a classic **heap leak** in the order processing module, and it's a very common one for those who forget to tell the memory to go home!\n\nFirst, let's look at the culprit: `new Order(orderId, price);`. This is where the leak happens. You're creating a new `Order` object on the heap, but you're not giving it a way to say goodbye to the heap. In C++, if you don't use a smart pointer (like `std::unique_ptr` or `std::shared_ptr`), the object stays alive until the end of the program, or until the stack frame is destroyed, which is often too late.\n\nNow, let's talk about the **goblin** who lives in the `Order` class. Imagine the `Order` class is a goblin who loves to eat up all the resources (memory) in the world. If you just give him a piece of paper (a raw pointer) and say \"go eat,\" he will happily eat up all the memory in the entire program, leaving nothing for the rest of the world.\n\nTo stop the goblin from eating up all the memory, you need to",
